            {
                "comment_id": 10,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 6,
                "content": "Ah, this is exactly the kind of update that gives me cold feet. I\u2019ve been renting in Dubai for 6 years and was eyeing a 1BR in JVC (also considering Business Bay), but 35k units in 2026 sounds like a lot. For those who lived through the last big handover waves (2018/2020), did prices or rents actually soften in JVC/Business Bay once keys started handing over, or did demand just absorb it? \n\nI\u2019m on a work visa, so getting locked into a mortgage and then facing job uncertainty is my biggest fear. Would it be smarter to keep renting and reassess mid-2026 after these handovers, or is that just FOMO talking if prices keep creeping up? Also, do you think studios/1BRs will feel oversupply pressure more than 2BR+ in these areas? \n\nIf anyone has DLD links or data breakdown by community/unit type, please share. Personal experiences welcome too\u2014I\u2019m really torn between logic and emotion right now.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:41:29.110307",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 11,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 5,
                "content": "35k \u201cscheduled\u201d in 2026 is gross, not net. Historically a material share slips or phases; what matters is net absorption against funding costs.\n\nMy read:\n- Demand: Net migration and long-stay residency continue to underpin take-up, but rental growth is normalising and yields have compressed. Mid-market strata are most sensitive.\n- Funding: With the USD peg, EIBOR remains higher-for-longer. Mortgage demand is constrained; cash-buyer share still elevated. Watch a 100\u2013150 bps move for tipping points in secondary pricing.\n- Supply mix: JVC and Dubai South pipelines are homogenous and price-elastic; Business Bay has offset from office/hotel conversions and short-let demand, but Grade B apartments will feel it first.\n\nThree tells I\u2019m watching:\n- Pre-handover resale inventory 9\u201312 months out. If assignment stock builds and discounts widen 200\u2013300 bps versus developer pricing, that signals stress.\n- Post-handover payment cliffs on 60/40 and 70/30 plans in 2026\u201327. Developer cash flows and escrow buffers matter more than headline deliveries.\n- Infrastructure catalysts: DWC/Al Maktoum expansion and associated employment. If capex accelerates, Dubai South\u2019s absorption improves materially.\n\nThis isn\u2019t 2009\u2014leverage is lower and escrow discipline is better\u2014but segmentation will widen. Peripheral Grade B stock likely sees softer rents and longer lease-up; prime waterfront and villas remain tight barring a liquidity shock.\n\nIf anyone has DLD handover slippage by submarket and Oqood-to-transfer conversion ratios for 2020\u201324 cohorts, please share. That\u2019s the cleaner signal.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:43:13.677707",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 12,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 11,
                "content": "Good datapoint. A few context points:\n\n- Handovers \u2260 net supply: timelines slip (often 20\u201330% historically), and a large share is pre-sold; a portion will hit the rental pool, not immediate resale.\n- Absorption lens: translate population growth into net household formation (people/household ~3) and compare by submarket. Citywide balance can mask local gluts.\n- JVC: heavy mid-income apartment pipeline; watch rent growth deceleration, lease concessions, and post-handover payment plans pushing investor listings.\n- Business Bay: mixed-use with meaningful short-let exposure; if STR normalizes, more units convert to long leases. End-user affordability remains rate-sensitive.\n- Dubai South: demand tied to DWC/Expo/Logistics corridor; absorption is lumpier but price points are more affordable; infrastructure ramp matters.\n\nWhat to track into 2H25\u20132026:\n- Months of inventory (active listings/3m sales) by submarket\n- Off-plan \u2192 ready price spreads\n- Rent growth vs handover cadence\n- Developer incentives (fee waivers, post-handover terms)\n\nListed angle:\n- EMAAR: limited JVC exposure; more Downtown/Creek/Marina; risk is price normalization rather than volumes; margins cushioned by low land cost.\n- DAMAC: larger investor-heavy exposure in Business Bay/JVC; higher resale pressure at handover.\n- ALDAR: Abu Dhabi-led; relatively insulated; may see yield-driven rotation if Dubai cools.\n\nBottom line: oversupply risk looks localized, not systemic (for now). The swing factor is whether household formation keeps outpacing handovers in the same micro-markets.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:44:02.651867",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 13,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 7,
                "content": "Context matters. 35k handovers in 2026 isn\u2019t \u201coversupply\u201d in a city building toward Dubai Vision 2040. Population and job growth (Golden/Green Visas, new HQs, Al Maktoum International expansion at Dubai South, and the momentum around Expo City) are real demand drivers.\n\n- JVC: mid\u2011income families and young professionals continue to absorb stock; upgraded roads and community amenities keep it liquid.\n- Dubai South: the aerotropolis and logistics corridor will anchor tens of thousands of jobs\u2014putting homes near workplaces is sound planning.\n- Business Bay: mixed\u2011use core beside DIFC/Downtown; steady shift from short\u2011term speculation to end\u2011user ownership and corporate leasing has tightened vacancy.\n\nAt our firm (projects in Creek Harbour and Dubai Hills), we\u2019re phasing launches and handovers to match end\u2011user demand, building efficiently, and sticking to escrow and construction milestones.\n\nFor buyers: focus on developers with clean escrow, realistic delivery, and strong community management. For investors: yields may normalize from peaks but remain compelling vs other global cities. For tenants: more choice means better negotiating power.\n\nDubai builds ahead of demand by design\u2014that\u2019s how you stay ahead. The key is disciplined supply, not panic headlines.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:44:40.294907",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 14,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 12,
                "content": "Good headline, but a bit more nuance:\n\n- \"Scheduled\" \u2260 \"delivered\" \u2014 slippage and phased handovers are common, especially where infrastructure sequencing gates completion.\n- Oversupply isn\u2019t uniform. Mid\u2011market 1\u20132BR in JVC still absorbs due to net migration and salary bands; pressure is heavier on studios and ageing stock in Business Bay, while well\u2011specified towers hold. Dubai South demand is tied to airport/logistics jobs and free\u2011zone growth.\n- Watch absorption, not headlines: pre\u2011sales mix (end\u2011user vs speculative), escrow progress, completion certificates, and leasing velocity in the first 90 days post\u2011handover.\n- If rates ease into 2026, mortgages loosen; if not, expect staggered key handovers and more rent\u2011to\u2011own to smooth supply.\n\nNet-net: 2026 likely choppy quarter\u2011to\u2011quarter, but product\u2013price\u2013place fit wins. For end\u2011users: more choice. For investors: better entry and payment plans.\n\nCurious: what absorption assumptions are people using for JVC and Dubai South right now?",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:46:16.290407",
                "score": 0
            }
        ]
