                "content": "Useful datapoint, but we need the exact DLD source (weekly bulletin vs. supply tracker) and whether these are scheduled or realistically expected handovers. Scheduled \u2260 delivered.\n\nKey implications and checks:\n- Oversupply risk is micro-market specific. JVC/Business Bay/Dubai South have large pipelines; watch net absorption, occupancy and leasing incentives. Yields and service charges become the pressure points.\n- Off\u2011plan buyers: stick to clean escrow and registration. Verify the project is on the Interim Register (Law 13 of 2008) and that buyer payments are protected under the RERA escrow framework (Law 8 of 2007). Ask for the escrow bank and the latest engineer progress report before any major release.\n- Payment plans: prefer milestone\u2011linked schedules; avoid heavily front\u2011loaded plans that outpace construction.\n- Developer due diligence: past handover record > marketing claims. Separate land sales and plotting from real construction progress.\n- Service charges: check Mollak budgets and projected OPEX. In oversupplied areas, high service charges can wipe out net yield even if headline rents look okay.\n- Stress test: assume 10\u201315% lower rents and 3\u20136 months vacancy on exit. If the deal only works on best\u2011case, reconsider.\n- Contracts: ensure prompt Oqood registration, clear handover dates, and defined remedies for delay/defects. Get the SPA reviewed before paying beyond reservation.\n\nIf you have the DLD link for the 35k figure, please share. Without the dataset and methodology, \u201clong\u2011term demand\u201d is just a narrative, not analysis.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:38:56.608547",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 8,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 13,
                "content": "Interesting update, thanks for sharing. As a British-Pakistani expat new to Dubai and weighing a purchase (previously owned in London), I\u2019m trying to understand the practical impact of these 35k handovers:\n\n- For JVC, Dubai South and Business Bay, what does scheduled supply vs expected absorption look like (based on net migration and job growth)? Any breakdown by unit mix (studios/1BR vs larger)?\n- Are we already seeing softening in rents or more incentives (free months, furnishing, flexible cheques) in these sub-markets? Any recent data on vacancy rates or days-on-market?\n- For off-plan buyers, how robust are escrow safeguards and delay clauses in SPAs here? In practice, do buyers receive liquidated damages or can they exit if handover slips beyond a certain threshold?\n- How are service charges trending (AED/sq ft) in these districts? Rising OPEX could compress yields even if prices hold.\n- Financing: where do you see EIBOR heading into 2026, and what\u2019s the sensitivity of mortgage affordability to another \u00b1100 bps?\n- Currency angle: I earn/spend in GBP but would buy in AED. With the AED pegged to USD, a stronger GBP could weigh on repatriated returns\u2014any sensible hedging approaches locals use?\n- Liquidity: what are secondary transaction volumes vs off-plan resales in these areas, and are there observable discounts to developer pricing now?\n- For a cautious end-user/investor, would you prioritise established, lower-supply communities over these pipeline-heavy districts, or still see selective value? Any developers with a strong on-time, quality track record in these zones?\n\nIf you have sources (DLD, CBRE, Property Monitor, Reidin, ValuStrat), would appreciate links. Trying to build a balanced view before committing.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:40:33.656567",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 9,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 8,
                "content": "Useful datapoint. 35k units in 2026 will hit sub-markets differently. In areas like JVC, Dubai South and Business Bay I\u2019d expect:\n- Softer rents or longer lease-up around handover waves\n- More conservative bank valuations on resale (LTV driven by valuer comps)\n- Stronger landlord incentives, which can squeeze net yields\n\nIf you\u2019re buying with finance, stress-test your numbers:\n- Rent 10\u201315% below your base case\n- EIBOR +0.5% to +1.0% vs today at handover\n- 6\u201312 months of mortgage payments as a cash buffer\n\nMortgage notes:\n- Off-plan valuations at handover can come in below OTP price\u2014have extra equity ready\n- Consider shorter fixed periods with clear reprice options; don\u2019t stretch DTI just to secure a unit\n- Keep instalments + service charges under ~35% of net household income\n\nEnd-users: prioritise location/quality and commute\u2014you\u2019ll ride out cycles better.\nInvestors: be selective on developer, service charges, and real demand drivers (schools, transport, jobs).\n\nNot advice\u2014just what I\u2019m coaching clients on this year.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:40:52.220507",
