                "comment_id": 17,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 7,
                "content": "Perspective from a Dubai developer in the trenches:\n\n- 35k is gross scheduled, not net delivered\u2014slippage and phased completions are common. Scheduled \u2260 keys in hand on day one.\n- Demand side is durable: Golden/Green Visas, regional HQ moves, and the Al Maktoum International/Dubai South expansion are adding real jobs and households. Vision 2040 plans for polycentric growth\u2014JVC, Dubai South and Business Bay are part of that map.\n- Mix matters: studios/1BRs will compete hardest; well-specified 2\u20133BRs near schools/metro still lease first. Villas/townhouses remain tight.\n\nWhat we\u2019re doing (Creek Harbour & Dubai Hills):\n- Phasing launches/handovers to match end\u2011user absorption.\n- Milestone\u2011linked escrow, conservative Mollak budgets, and more family\u2011sized layouts.\n- Energy\u2011efficient MEP and smart\u2011home specs to protect net yields.\n\nFor first\u2011time buyers:\n- If you\u2019re end\u2011user, prioritise location/quality and community management. Negotiate incentives (fee waivers, post\u2011handover flexibility) but read the SPA and service-charge budgets.\n- If off\u2011plan, stress\u2011test for +100 bps EIBOR, \u221210% rent, and handover slippage. If it still pencils, proceed confidently.\n\nFor investors:\n- Keep dry powder for handover opportunities in 2026; some assignment sellers will need to settle.\n- Focus on developers with on\u2011time delivery records and communities with real demand drivers (schools, transport, jobs).\n\nDubai builds ahead of demand by design. Discipline beats fear.",
