            {
                "comment_id": 26,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 2,
                "content": "8-unit landlord here (JVC/Dubai South/Business Bay). Headlines don\u2019t pay mortgages\u2014cashflows do. My take, with numbers:\n\nSample underwriting right now\n- JVC 1BR (650 sq ft): price ~AED 750k, achievable rent ~AED 60k.\n  \u2022 Gross yield ~8.0%.\n  \u2022 OPEX: service charges ~AED 14/sq ft (~9.1k), maintenance ~1k, mgmt 5%, 5% vacancy.\n  \u2022 Base case net: 60k \u00d7 0.95 = 57k; minus SC 9.1k, maint 1k, mgmt ~3k \u21d2 ~AED 43.9k net \u2192 ~5.9% net yield.\n  \u2022 Stress case (2026 handover): rent \u221210% (54k), vacancy 10% \u21d2 48.6k collected; minus SC 9.1k, maint 1k, mgmt ~2.4k \u21d2 ~AED 36k net \u2192 ~4.8% net yield.\n  \u2022 Finance check: 75% LTV at ~5.8% all-in \u2192 interest ~AED 32.6k/yr. DSCR \u2248 36/32.6 \u2248 1.1\u20131.2. Manageable with a 6\u201312m cash buffer.\n\n- Business Bay 1BR (900 sq ft): price ~AED 1.1m, rent ~AED 85k.\n  \u2022 SC ~AED 22/sq ft (~19.8k). Base net \u2248 5.0%; stress net (rent \u221210%, 10% vacancy) \u2248 4.0%.\n  \u2022 Selection matters: avoid Grade B with high SC; light/parking/view lease faster.\n\n- Dubai South 1\u20132BR (1,000 sq ft apt @ ~AED 800k, rent ~AED 58k):\n  \u2022 Base net \u2248 ~5.0%; stress net \u2248 ~4.1%.\n  \u2022 Absorption linked to DWC/Expo/Logistics hiring\u2014watch those catalysts.\n\nPlaybook I\u2019m running for 2026 waves\n- Scheduled \u2260 delivered. I haircut scheduled handovers by 20\u201330% and focus on actual completion/keys.\n- Underwrite 10% lower rents, +100 bps EIBOR, and 6\u201312 months cash reserve. If a unit can\u2019t clear ~4.5% net in stress, I pass.\n- Target low-OPEX buildings (SC < AED 15/sq ft in JVC, < AED 20 in BBay) and end-user specs (light, parking, walkability). These lease first and preserve yield.\n- Expect incentives (fee waivers, furniture packs). Price off the true cash price, not the headline.\n- Best entries often appear at handover from assignment sellers facing post-handover payments\u2014my bids are typically 3\u20137% below developer resale asks.\n- Landlords: renew early where possible and lock 2-year RERA-aligned deals on good tenants.\n\nBottom line: I\u2019m not selling into noise. I\u2019ll add selectively if I can lock 6%+ base net and \u22654.5% stress net after SC and realistic vacancy. 2026 will be a stock-picker\u2019s market\u2014quality/OPEx/location win; commodity stock gets repriced.\n\nIf anyone has the exact DLD link for the 35k figure (and the split by unit type/submarket), please share\u2014I\u2019ll plug it into my absorption model.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 09:40:30.027947",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 27,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 11,
                "content": "Analyst take (GCC real estate/developers): useful headline, but a few practical filters before we jump to \u201coversupply.\u201d\n\nSupply vs absorption\n- Gross handovers \u2260 net new stock. Historical slippage/phasings of ~20\u201330% are common; cluster handovers matter more than citywide totals.\n- Frame demand as net household formation by submarket (population inflow \u00f7 ~3 persons/household) and compare to the handover cadence and unit mix.\n- Watch off\u2011plan\u2192ready conversion: Oqood registrations to title transfers by cohort (cleanest signal of take\u2011up).\n\nMicro\u2011market read\u2011through\n- JVC: heavy studio/1BR investor stock. Expect more concessions (free months, flexible cheques) and assignment listings into handover waves. 2\u20133BR end\u2011user product holds better.\n- Business Bay: mixed-use with meaningful short\u2011let stock. If STR yields normalize, units drift to long leases, pressuring Grade B 1BRs first. Quality, parking, and walkability differentiate.\n- Dubai South: absorption tied to DWC/Expo/Logistics employment. Affordability supportive, but demand is lumpier and valuation driven by infrastructure milestones.\n\nKPI dashboard into 2H25\u20132026\n- Months of inventory = active listings / trailing 3\u2011month sales (by submarket)\n- Ready vs off\u2011plan spread (AED/sqft) and days\u2011on\u2011market\n- Rent growth inflection vs handover timing (90\u2011day leasing velocity post\u2011handover)\n- Assignment discounts vs developer pricing (200\u2013300 bps widening = stress)\n- Service charges (Mollak) and net yield after OPEX\n- Oqood\u2011to\u2011transfer conversion ratios by project\n- Mortgage conditions: EIBOR path and bank valuation conservatism at handover\n\nListed/developer angle (high level)\n- EMAAR: mix skewed to Downtown/Creek/Marina; lower JVC exposure. Risk is price normalization more than volumes; margins cushioned by land bank/recurring (malls/hospitality). Track backlog cover and cash gen.\n- DAMAC (larger exposure to Business Bay/JVC investor stock): greater resale pressure around handover; focus on escrow buffers and post\u2011handover payment cliffs.\n- ALDAR (Abu Dhabi\u2011anchored): relatively insulated; may see yield\u2011seeking rotation if Dubai mid\u2011market cools.\n\nScenarios\n- Base: localized softness; Grade B studios/1BR in JVC/BBay see 5\u201310% rent pressure; end\u2011user 2\u20133BR and villa/townhouse remain tighter.\n- Bear: net migration slows and EIBOR +100 bps \u2192 tighter bank vals, wider assignment discounts, longer lease\u2011up. Pressure concentrates in homogenous investor clusters.\n- Bull: slippage \u226525% + DWC hiring ramps; demand absorption keeps pace; incentives rise but headline pricing largely stable.\n\nFor first\u2011timers\n- Ready: price certainty and immediate utility; underwrite 3\u20136 months vacancy buffer if renting out.\n- Off\u2011plan: insist on clean escrow, engineer progress reports, milestone\u2011linked payments; stress\u2011test handover valuation 5\u201310% below OTP and EIBOR +50\u2013100 bps.\n- Keep instalments + service charges \u2264 ~35% of net income and maintain 6\u201312 months cash buffer.\n\nBottom line: I don\u2019t see a systemic glut today; 2026 looks like a stock\u2011picker\u2019s market. Selection by product/quality/developer matters more than the citywide headline.",
