            },
            {
                "comment_id": 21,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 8,
                "content": "For the anxious first\u2011timers here, a practical lens from a Dubai mortgage broker:\n\nWhat usually happens around big handover waves (JVC, Dubai South, Business Bay):\n- More landlord/developer incentives and longer lease\u2011up for studios/1BRs; better buildings still lease/sell first.\n- Valuers get conservative. You may qualify for 80% LTV on paper, but the bank lends off valuation, not asking price.\n\nReady vs off\u2011plan (2026 lens):\n- Ready: price is clearer, you can inspect the asset, and finance immediately. Downside: you pay today\u2019s rate and fees upfront.\n- Off\u2011plan: smaller staged payments now but risk that handover valuation < OTP price. Post\u2011handover balloons (60/40, 70/30) can bite in 2026\u201327 if EIBOR stays elevated. Delivery can slip.\n\nMortgage specifics to plan for:\n- LTV: Expats typically max 80% for a first home; banks won\u2019t cut statutory caps for \u201coversupply\u201d, but valuation haircuts of 2\u20135% are common in crowded sub\u2011markets. Keep 5\u201310% extra equity handy for a shortfall at handover.\n- Rate stress test: Model EIBOR +0.5% to +1.0% vs today at your completion date. Rough guide: every 100 bps adds ~AED 600\u2013650 per month per AED 1m over 25 years.\n- Affordability: Keep total housing (mortgage + service charges + insurance) under ~35\u201340% of net household income. UAE DBR cap is 50%\u2014don\u2019t run that hot.\n- Buffer: Hold 6\u201312 months of instalments in cash. If your job security is variable, stay toward the high end.\n- Fix vs variable: If you\u2019re risk\u2011averse, consider a 2\u20133 year fixed with known exit fees; avoid long fixes if you might sell/ prepay early. Variable can work only if your budget handles swings.\n\nTiming guidance (not one\u2011size\u2011fits\u2011all):\n- If you\u2019re shopping commodity studios/1BRs in JVC/Business Bay, waiting 6\u201312 months could improve your choice and negotiating power as keys land.\n- If you need a well\u2011specified 2BR+ in a quality, lower\u2011supply community you\u2019ll live in for 5+ years, focus on the right unit rather than the calendar.\n\nDue diligence checklist:\n- Service charges (Mollak) and OPEX trends\u2014high charges can erase yield/affordability.\n- Developer/escrow health, engineer progress reports, Interim Register status.\n- Cluster risk: multiple buildings in the same block handing over the same quarter.\n- Ask brokers for pre\u2011handover assignment inventory and discount to developer pricing.\n\nSimple decision rule of thumb:\n- If buy vs rent cost gap is small (<10%) and you have the cash buffer, stable income, and 5+ year horizon, buying a good ready unit is reasonable.\n- If you\u2019re stretching DTI or banking on best\u2011case rent/valuation, keep renting and reassess mid\u20112026.\n\nHappy to sanity\u2011check numbers if you share budget, income and unit type. Not advice\u2014just how I\u2019m coaching clients this year.",
