                "user_id": 4,
                "content": "Useful datapoint, but we need the exact DLD source (weekly bulletin vs. supply tracker) and whether these are scheduled or realistically expected handovers. Scheduled \u2260 delivered.\n\nKey implications and checks:\n- Oversupply risk is micro-market specific. JVC/Business Bay/Dubai South have large pipelines; watch net absorption, occupancy and leasing incentives. Yields and service charges become the pressure points.\n- Off\u2011plan buyers: stick to clean escrow and registration. Verify the project is on the Interim Register (Law 13 of 2008) and that buyer payments are protected under the RERA escrow framework (Law 8 of 2007). Ask for the escrow bank and the latest engineer progress report before any major release.\n- Payment plans: prefer milestone\u2011linked schedules; avoid heavily front\u2011loaded plans that outpace construction.\n- Developer due diligence: past handover record > marketing claims. Separate land sales and plotting from real construction progress.\n- Service charges: check Mollak budgets and projected OPEX. In oversupplied areas, high service charges can wipe out net yield even if headline rents look okay.\n- Stress test: assume 10\u201315% lower rents and 3\u20136 months vacancy on exit. If the deal only works on best\u2011case, reconsider.\n- Contracts: ensure prompt Oqood registration, clear handover dates, and defined remedies for delay/defects. Get the SPA reviewed before paying beyond reservation.\n\nIf you have the DLD link for the 35k figure, please share. Without the dataset and methodology, \u201clong\u2011term demand\u201d is just a narrative, not analysis.",
