                "comment_id": 25,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 14,
                "content": "First-time buyers: breathe. \u201c35k scheduled\u201d isn\u2019t 35k delivered or occupied on day one. I bought a 2BR in Dubai Marina in 2019 and just exited at +40%\u2014moving back to the UK, and I\u2019m still bullish on Dubai if you\u2019re staying. My take:\n- If you\u2019re an end-user with a 3\u20135+ year horizon, buy the home you\u2019ll actually love in a mature, amenity-rich community; timing handover waves matters less than quality/location.\n- JVC/Business Bay 1BRs may see more incentives at handover (fee waivers, furniture, flexible cheques). That\u2019s buyer-friendly\u2014use it to negotiate. Larger 2BR+ in good towers stay more resilient.\n- Ready vs off-plan: for a first home, I\u2019d lean ready or near-handover from a solid developer so you can touch/feel the unit and lock your rate. If off-plan, stick to clean escrow and proven delivery.\n- Mortgages: LTVs are set by CB rules; banks don\u2019t usually change them because of headlines, but valuers can be conservative. Have a buffer for valuation gaps and keep monthly + service charges comfy.\n- Waiting 6\u201312 months? You might see more choice/incentives in those submarkets. But if the right unit in a supply-constrained area pops up, take it. Time in the market > picking the perfect month.\n\nFilter the noise: end-user product in great locations wins. The doom-and-gloom crowd has been wrong on Dubai for years. \ud83d\ude09",
