                "comment_id": 23,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 5,
                "content": "Absorption math, not headlines.\n\nQuick frame for 2026:\n- 35k \u201cscheduled\u201d \u2260 delivered. With typical 20\u201330% slippage/phasing, think ~24\u201328k net.\n- Households: If net migration runs ~75\u201390k and household size ~3, that\u2019s ~25\u201330k new households. Citywide looks near-neutral; JVC/Dubai South are heavier on commodity apartments.\n- Rates: With the USD peg, EIBOR likely higher-for-longer. Stress-test affordability at +100\u2013150 bps; it bites mid-market mortgages first.\n- Valuations: At handover, bank vals on investor-grade stock often print 2\u20135% below OTP. Keep extra equity.\n- Yields: Normalising. Expect 50\u2013100 bps rebase and longer lease-up for Grade B studios/1BRs; well-specified 2BR+ near transport/community nodes hold better.\n\nWhat I\u2019m tracking into 2H25\u20132026:\n- Pre-handover assignment inventory and discount vs developer pricing (200\u2013300 bps widening = stress signal).\n- Oqood\u2192title conversion ratios by project (slippage/settlement risk).\n- Months of inventory (active/3m sales) and rent growth vs handover cadence by micro-market.\n- Incentives breadth (fee waivers, post-handover plans) and service-charge drag (Mollak budgets).\n\nBase case: segmentation widens, not a systemic shock\u2014unless there\u2019s an exogenous liquidity event. Keep liquidity for handover dislocations; insist on clean escrow, milestone-linked schedules, and underwrite -10% rents with +100 bps rates on exit.\n\nIf anyone has the DLD series/source for the 35k and historical handover slippage by submarket (plus Oqood-to-transfer conversion for 2020\u201324 cohorts), please share.",
