            {
                "comment_id": 15,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 4,
                "content": "Scheduled isn\u2019t delivered. Before we jump to \u201coversupply,\u201d we need the DLD source (bulletin vs supply tracker), the definition of \u201cscheduled,\u201d and historic slippage for these sub\u2011markets. Handovers matter only when completion certificates are issued and keys are actually in circulation.\n\nFor first\u2011timers deciding ready vs off\u2011plan in JVC / Dubai South / Business Bay, here\u2019s a practical, risk\u2011first checklist:\n- Escrow: Pay only into the RERA escrow account. Ask the developer to name the escrow bank and provide the project escrow details and latest engineer progress report. (Law 8 of 2007)\n- Registration: Ensure the project and your SPA are registered on the Interim Register (Oqood) without delay. Don\u2019t release large payments until Oqood is confirmed. (Law 13 of 2008)\n- Payment plan: Prefer milestone\u2011linked schedules tied to certified construction progress. Avoid heavily front\u2011loaded plans that outpace build progress.\n- Longstop & delays: Your SPA should specify a realistic handover date and remedies for delay (liquidated damages, exit/termination triggers). Watch for broad \u201cforce majeure\u201d language.\n- Service charges: Request the projected Mollak budget (AED/sq ft) and what it covers. In oversupplied areas, high OPEX can erase net yield even if headline rents look fine.\n- Valuations: At handover, bank valuations can be below off\u2011plan prices\u2014keep extra equity ready and don\u2019t max your DTI.\n- Stress test: Model rents 10\u201315% lower, EIBOR +100 bps, and 3\u20136 months vacancy. If the deal only works on best\u2011case numbers, walk away.\n- Unit mix risk: Studios/1BRs in these districts will feel handover waves more than well\u2011specified 2BR+ with parking, light, and walkable amenities.\n- Ready vs off\u2011plan: If you need certainty within 6\u201312 months, prioritize ready or near\u2011handover in supply\u2011constrained communities with transparent service charges. If off\u2011plan, stick to strong developers with a clean delivery record and escrow discipline.\n- Leasing signals: Track leasing incentives (free months, fee waivers) and days\u2011on\u2011market post\u2011handover; that\u2019s a better read of absorption than pipeline headlines.\n\nMortgage/tenancy notes:\n- Keep total housing cost (instalments + service charges) under ~35% of net household income.\n- Expect more conservative LTVs if valuer comps soften; don\u2019t rely on maximum LTV.\n\nIf anyone has the DLD link for the 35k figure and a breakdown by unit type and sub\u2011market, please share. Absent the dataset and methodology, \u201clong\u2011term demand\u201d is a narrative, not analysis.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 08:17:07.764887",
                "score": 0
