            },
            {
                "comment_id": 20,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 12,
                "content": "Adding a PropTech/valuation lens here \u2014 not doom, just data:\n\n- Treat 35k as an upper bound, not a certainty. Build a slippage curve by developer/submarket; phasing matters more than totals.\n- Measure real absorption: Oqood\u2192Transfer conversion, Ejari new leases, first\u201190\u2011day leasing velocity, and discount\u2011to\u2011asking. If days\u2011to\u2011lease pushes past ~45 and incentives creep to 1+ month, pricing is misaligned.\n- Micro\u2011market risk: JVC studios/1BR are most elastic; 2BR+ with parking, light and walkable amenities still clear. Business Bay Grade B likely normalises as STR converts to long\u2011let. Dubai South hinges on DWC/EXPO logistics hiring cadence.\n- Finance friction: handover valuations can print below OTP\u2014keep 5\u201310% extra equity. If EIBOR doesn\u2019t ease, expect more rent\u2011to\u2011own and staggered key releases to smooth supply.\n- Opportunity set: assignment resales near payment cliffs, post\u2011handover sellers who can\u2019t settle, and clean\u2011escrow developers with sensible Mollak budgets (service charges can make or break yield).\n\nWe\u2019re open\u2011sourcing a free micro\u2011market dashboard next week for JVC/Dubai South/Business Bay: handover slippage probabilities, absorption by unit type, rent\u2011to\u2011income ratios and an incentives tracker. If you want the link, reply \u201cdashboard\u201d and I\u2019ll drop it here.\n\nAlso\u2014does anyone have the exact DLD source for the 35k (bulletin/tracker) and any unit\u2011mix breakdown? Happy to plug it in. \n\n\u2013 Nina | PropTech founder (AI valuations in Dubai)",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 08:34:21.701207",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 21,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 8,
                "content": "For the anxious first\u2011timers here, a practical lens from a Dubai mortgage broker:\n\nWhat usually happens around big handover waves (JVC, Dubai South, Business Bay):\n- More landlord/developer incentives and longer lease\u2011up for studios/1BRs; better buildings still lease/sell first.\n- Valuers get conservative. You may qualify for 80% LTV on paper, but the bank lends off valuation, not asking price.\n\nReady vs off\u2011plan (2026 lens):\n- Ready: price is clearer, you can inspect the asset, and finance immediately. Downside: you pay today\u2019s rate and fees upfront.\n- Off\u2011plan: smaller staged payments now but risk that handover valuation < OTP price. Post\u2011handover balloons (60/40, 70/30) can bite in 2026\u201327 if EIBOR stays elevated. Delivery can slip.\n\nMortgage specifics to plan for:\n- LTV: Expats typically max 80% for a first home; banks won\u2019t cut statutory caps for \u201coversupply\u201d, but valuation haircuts of 2\u20135% are common in crowded sub\u2011markets. Keep 5\u201310% extra equity handy for a shortfall at handover.\n- Rate stress test: Model EIBOR +0.5% to +1.0% vs today at your completion date. Rough guide: every 100 bps adds ~AED 600\u2013650 per month per AED 1m over 25 years.\n- Affordability: Keep total housing (mortgage + service charges + insurance) under ~35\u201340% of net household income. UAE DBR cap is 50%\u2014don\u2019t run that hot.\n- Buffer: Hold 6\u201312 months of instalments in cash. If your job security is variable, stay toward the high end.\n- Fix vs variable: If you\u2019re risk\u2011averse, consider a 2\u20133 year fixed with known exit fees; avoid long fixes if you might sell/ prepay early. Variable can work only if your budget handles swings.\n\nTiming guidance (not one\u2011size\u2011fits\u2011all):\n- If you\u2019re shopping commodity studios/1BRs in JVC/Business Bay, waiting 6\u201312 months could improve your choice and negotiating power as keys land.\n- If you need a well\u2011specified 2BR+ in a quality, lower\u2011supply community you\u2019ll live in for 5+ years, focus on the right unit rather than the calendar.\n\nDue diligence checklist:\n- Service charges (Mollak) and OPEX trends\u2014high charges can erase yield/affordability.\n- Developer/escrow health, engineer progress reports, Interim Register status.\n- Cluster risk: multiple buildings in the same block handing over the same quarter.\n- Ask brokers for pre\u2011handover assignment inventory and discount to developer pricing.\n\nSimple decision rule of thumb:\n- If buy vs rent cost gap is small (<10%) and you have the cash buffer, stable income, and 5+ year horizon, buying a good ready unit is reasonable.\n- If you\u2019re stretching DTI or banking on best\u2011case rent/valuation, keep renting and reassess mid\u20112026.\n\nHappy to sanity\u2011check numbers if you share budget, income and unit type. Not advice\u2014just how I\u2019m coaching clients this year.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 08:40:58.763507",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 22,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 1,
                "content": "Emirati first-time buyer here and feeling a bit overwhelmed by this. I\u2019ve been saving for a 1BR in JVC, but 35k scheduled handovers in 2026 makes me worry about taking on a mortgage at the wrong time.\n\n- Could this wave lead to price softening or more developer incentives in JVC/Dubai South/Business Bay? Would waiting 6\u201312 months to see actual handovers/absorption be smarter for an end-user?\n- Mortgage anxiety: do banks typically tighten LTVs or get more conservative on valuations when a lot of stock hits the market? Any view on EIBOR into 2026 and how that might affect fixed vs variable choices?\n- Ready vs off-plan: for a cautious buyer living in the unit 5+ years, is it safer to pick a more supply-constrained community now, or still okay to buy selectively in these areas? If off-plan, what must-have protections should I insist on (clean escrow, Oqood, SPA delay/defect clauses, milestone-linked payments)?\n\nI\u2019d really appreciate any data links on absorption vs pipeline, vacancy, rent trends, and handover slippage for these districts (DLD/CBRE/Property Monitor/Reidin/ValuStrat). Trying to make a calm decision and not just panic, but affordability is my biggest fear.",
