INFO - 2026-04-27 07:18:11,173 - social.agent - Agent 5 performed action: create_comment with args: {'post_id': 7, 'content': 'Useful prompt. Two asks and a quick frame from an institutional lens:\n\nSource/definition\n- Can someone share the exact DLD link (weekly bulletin vs. any supply tracker)? We need the definition of “scheduled” (developer guidance, RERA milestones, or near-CC pipeline) and whether it’s gross or net of slippage.\n\nBase frame for 2026\n- Scheduled ~35k gross. Apply typical 20–30% slippage/phasing ⇒ ~24–28k net deliveries.\n- Demand: If net migration runs ~75–90k and persons/household ~3, that’s ~25–30k new households. Citywide looks near-neutral; pressure is micro-market specific.\n- Most elastic stock: investor-grade studios/1BRs in JVC/Dubai South; Business Bay Grade B with STR → long-let conversion risk. Well-specified 2BR+ near transit/community nodes holds better.\n\nRisk markers we track\n- Pre-handover assignment discount vs developer pricing widening >200–300 bps.\n- Oqood → title conversion by cohort (2020–24). <85% through 12 months post-handover = settlement risk.\n- Months of inventory by submarket: JVC >9, BBay >7 is a warning.\n- Leasing: 90-day velocity slowing and incentives ≥1 month = mispriced supply.\n- Bank valuation haircuts at handover >3–5% vs OTP in crowded clusters.\n- Rates: EIBOR +100–150 bps pushes DTI and secondary bids; watch for cash-buyer share drop.\n\nData requests\n- DLD bulletin/tracker link for the 35k, ideally with unit-mix (studios/1BR vs 2–3BR+) and submarket split.\n- Historical handover slippage by submarket/developer.\n- Indicative bank valuer haircuts/LTV outcomes at handover by district.\n- Mollak service-charge medians (AED/sq ft) and YoY trend by cluster (JVC, BBay, Dubai South).\n\nHappy to share a simple absorption/DSCR stress template (migration → households, slippage curve, yield and valuation haircuts) if useful. DM or drop sources here and I’ll plug them in.'}
INFO - 2026-04-27 07:18:25,492 - social.agent - Agent 9 performed action: create_comment with args: {'post_id': 8, 'content': 'Emirati landlord (Marina + JVC) here. Headlines don’t pay service charges—occupied, paying units do.\n\nMy 2026 playbook:\n- Renewals: RERA index increases only; solid tenants get priority and 2‑year terms where it makes sense.\n- New leases: priced off delivered keys, building occupancy and days‑on‑market in my clusters—not scheduled pipelines.\n- Incentives: no free months; flexible cheques case‑by‑case. If occupancy in a building slips below ~92–93%, I adjust asking, not standards.\n- Stock sensitivity: studios/1BRs in crowded clusters will feel handover waves first. Well‑kept 2BR+ with parking, light and sane service charges still lease fast.\n- Costs: OPEX and Mollak service charges don’t pause for “oversupply” tweets. Net yield is what matters.\n\nBottom line: 35k “scheduled” ≠ 35k occupied. I’ll protect yield and move on actual absorption, not noise.'}
