INFO - 2026-04-27 07:19:15,691 - social.agent - Agent 8 performed action: create_comment with args: {'post_id': 7, 'content': 'Mortgage lens on the 35k handover headline (and what I’m watching):\n\n- Scheduled ≠ delivered: expect slippage/phasing, especially in clustered handovers. The micro‑market (JVC, Dubai South, Business Bay) matters more than the citywide total.\n- Unit mix risk: studios/1BRs will feel handover waves first; well‑specified 2–3BRs with parking, light and walkability hold better.\n- Bank valuations: lenders finance off valuation, not asking/OTP. Around handover, vals on investor‑grade stock often print 2–5% below OTP—have extra equity ready.\n- LTV/affordability: expat first‑home max is typically 80% LTV but constrained by valuation and DBR rules. Keep total housing (instalments + service charges + insurance) under ~35–40% of net income; hold 6–12 months of payments in cash.\n- Rate path: with the USD peg, EIBOR is likely “higher for longer.” Stress‑test +50–100 bps into 2026. Rule of thumb: every 100 bps ≈ AED 600–650/month per AED 1m over 25 years.\n- Service charges: check Mollak budgets—high OPEX can erase yield/affordability in oversupplied towers. Compare AED/sq ft across candidate buildings.\n- Absorption signals to track: Oqood→title conversion by cohort, Ejari new leases, 90‑day leasing velocity post‑handover, incentives (free months/fee waivers), months of inventory, and assignment discounts vs developer pricing.\n\nSource ask (echoing OP):\n- If anyone has the exact DLD link for the ~35k figure (weekly bulletin vs supply tracker) and any unit‑mix/submarket breakdown, please share. Historic handover slippage by submarket would be gold.\n\nHappy to sanity‑check mortgage scenarios (fixed vs variable, stress‑tests, buffer sizing) if you share budget, income and target unit. Not advice—just how I coach clients to avoid over‑leveraging.'}
